  "answer": "The critic misreads the standard. Clause (2) requires that forbidden cases be concrete observations that could realistically have obtained, not that they be formulated in a particular vocabulary. The first forbidden case is a concrete historical scenario: a demonstration that Egyptian central administration collapsed contemporaneously with territorial fragmentation on the scale of the Hittite or Mycenaean collapses. Such a demonstration would consist of specific archaeological and textual evidence (destruction layers, cessation of royal inscriptions, administrative abandonment) that either exists or does not. The second forbidden case demands evidence of robust private economic activity continuing without disruption in Ugarit or Hattusa during their palatial collapse periods — a concrete empirical claim that could be supported or refuted by archaeological records of merchant quarters, private archives, or production facilities showing continuity. The third forbidden case requires paleoclimatic data (e.g., pollen cores, speleothem records, sediment analyses) showing no significant climatic anomaly in the Eastern Mediterranean during 1200–1150 BC — a perfectly concrete, datable pattern that either appears in the empirical record or does not. All three cases specify observable, potentially obtainable states of the historical and environmental record; none requires counterfactual reasoning or vague evaluation."
